<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-01-27T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-01-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="268" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/4438: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Geissler</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-01-27T17:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January 27,
                                        1927—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>6. Legation’s telegram number 11, dated January 19, 8 a.m.<note n="29" xml:id="d268fn29">Not printed.</note> It is not the intention of the
                            Department to urge President Diaz to accept any foreign government’s
                            mediation to settle the differences between the Nicaraguan Government
                            and the revolutionary forces based on the withdrawal of both President
                            Diaz and Sacasa. You should make no more efforts to encourage the
                            Government of Guatemala to offer its good offices in connection with
                            this matter.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>